SUPLINF.P:
Under CAT coverage, the basic unit is established on ownership share and not by practice; 
i.e.
, field grown and containerized plants are combined into one basic unit. The basic unit cannot be subdivided into optional units.

Most nursery plants are started as liners; 
i.e.
, small plants produced in nursery trays or flats. As a plant matures, it is usually repotted, or upgraded, into a larger container or placed into the ground. The current nursery program only insures plant in container that are three inches or greater at the widest point of the container interior. This limitation precludes a significant segment of the nursery industry from crop insurance coverage. Insuring plants in containers down to one inch in diameter will provide coverage to the majority of liner plants produced by the nursery industry.

REGTEXT.P:
(j) Insurable plants in over-sized containers will be valued for purposes of reporting inventory and loss adjustment as if the plants were in appropriate-sized containers in accordance with the standards contained in the current American Standard for Nursery Stock. Each cell in a multiple-cell container is considered a separate container. (See the Eligible Plant List at 
http://www.rma.usda.gov/
 for additional information and requirements on container specifications and volume calculation.)
